76561197971460894,Not Recommended,252450,15492612,"Posted: 22 April, 2015",all,CD,"Disclaimer: This review focuses mostly on a comparison between StarDrive 1 and 2. If you're new to the series you can safely skip this text. A 'Tl;DR' summary can be found at the end of the review.I almost feel bad about giving this game a thumbs down. But since there is no ""it's just average"" option and I certainly can't go with a thumbs up, it'll have to do.StarDrive 1 with its free-flowing combat, RTS feeling and huge fleets was a nice change of pace. StarDrive 2 being turn-based came as a bit of a shock to me and took me out of the game almost instantly. On the other hand, if you're into more traditional 4X games you're probably fine with this change.Also gone are the huge fleets you could build in StarDrive 1. The number of ships is now (soft)capped by command points, which results in much smaller battles. But since even small and medium scale battles can have quite a severe impact on frame rate, this might not be a bad thing, at least not from a performance point of view. (I'm running an OC'ed i7 with two OC'ed GTX780s, not exactly a ""slow"" setup, but during battles the frame rate can drop to almost 0).Speaking of ships, there is now less variety - the smaller classes are mostly gone. So most races are down to four different classes, and again the Titans have no preset layout, so unless you don't supply the AI with your own layouts they won't build Titans (which further reduces the hull variety to three).Meanwhile, the ship editor has been reworked and streamlined: Similar weapons and components are now grouped together and you get nice diagrams showing you the range and damage output of each weapon. You can also set a default behaviour for each ship layout. Unfortunately you can no longer manually edit the firing arc of your turrets. Granted this was very fiddly in StarDrive 1 and I like the fact that the turrets default to either a bow or port/starboard firing arc. On the other hand, it would be nice to have the option to overwrite these default firing arcs. But all in all I think the ship editor has seen the most improvements compared to StarDrive 1, although you have less hulls (per race) to play with and all the remaining hulls (except for the two new races) are more or less directly copied from StarDrive 1.Speaking of ""copied from StarDrive 1"". A *lot* of stuff has been either directly copied from its predecessor or only slightly modified. Now I won't go on about this for too much, since as far as I'm aware these game were pretty much a one or two man operation... but I was still surprised by the amount of images, ships and weapons that were reused. I guess if you're new to StarDrive 2 then it doesn't really matter, but if you've played the original then there really isn't that much new content. (if we discount the fact that StarDrive 2 is turn-based it could almost be an addon for StarDrive 1 instead of a new game)Although, to be fair, there is now turn based ground combat (think of XCOM) which is kinda neat. But it doesn't feel fleshed out. Personally I would have kept ground combat the way it was in StarDrive 1 and focused development on other areas of the game. If I wanted in-depth turn-based squad combat I would play, well, XCOM. Luckily there is an auto-resolve option that lets you skip this part of the game.Talking about combat: space combat is of course still a big part of StarDrive 2, but you have to micromanage a lot more than in StarDrive 1 since there does not seem to any sort of ""attack-move"". Without input your ships will just sit at their spawn location. You have to manually assign targets because your ships won't automatically pick their own target (you can defince a ""typical behaviour"" in the ship editor but that only seems to affect the way the enemy AI is utilizing the ships).TL;DR:StarDrive 2 goes from RTS to turn-based. Fleet sizes seem to be severly limited due to a command point limit. Space combat is still in real time but you have to micromanage and babysit your ships a lot (which some people probably find appealing). A lot of the ingame art, ships and weapons have been lifted from StarDrive 1, and while the introduction of turn-based, XCOM-esque ground combat might set the game apart from other 4X games, I found it very tedious.On the plus side, the ship editor has been improved greatly and the game seems to be more stable (at least for me) than StarDrive 1.Again, I would give the game an average score if I could (but for now Steam is lacking this option). Overall I was hoping for a continuation of StarDrive 1 (think different hulls & weapons, new tech tree), but what I got was basically ""StarDrive 1 - the turn based edition""."
76561197995426074,Not Recommended,252450,16421361,"Posted: 15 June, 2015",all,calendyr,"Star Drive 2 looks like it would be a really good game.  Strong Master of Orion 2 resemblance and all.Unfortunatelly the developper believes that his customers are paying beta testers.  He realeases a game so buggy that it's almost unplayable.  Every aspect of the game from ground combat, planet capture, diplomacy, tech, UI, game balance  is buggy and/or flawed.To make matter worse, instead of working on fixes for those bugs, the dev is working on expansions for the game.  Dev never fixed the problem in Star Drive 1.  Seems like he decided to do the same in SD2.Just buy something else, this is a waste of money."
