76561197970967930,Not Recommended,252450,15319560,"Posted: 12 April, 2015",all,A Pimpfo named Info,"Update 2015-09-05:Decided to give this game a try again now when it's been around a while.An improvement becomes noticable quite quickly, namely that the guns are now more balanced so that you can no longer ""cheese with ease"" through any and all combats using artillery.Sadly, that seems to be the one actual improvement in the past months.Certainly there must be some minor tweaks, but the obnoxious lack of a proper AI guvernor is only outmatched by the AI's blatant cheap cheating.This game still has nice graphics going for it - But that is it. The programming for this is cheap and lazy. Money will be better spent on touched-up flash-games or 8-bit remakes rather than this, sadly.Now 2/10 for total lacking of engangement with both the game mechanics and the playerbase.Earlier review holds true:Short review - A simplified rewrap of Stardrive 1 which pulls away innovative features and improves on nothing but graphics.4/10 based upon how immersive the game felt measured against it's predecessor and the numerous disadvantages the second offers.More detailed review:First off, measuring it against it's predecessor, the starting menu itself is downgraded. No biggy, but made me raise an eyebrow seeing as how the first felt a lot more engaging.The empire-building is/feels a lot more restricted, especially with the old ""Masters of Orion favorite"" 'creative' now being added - Trait balancing for min-maxing is currently required for a playable longterm game.Entering the game itself, it is now fully turnbased - And nothing has been done to improve the UI. The tooltips are, in many cases, closer to 'flavor text' which is not useful.Instead of having conflict and strategy on the same map, a simple round circle has been applied where your ships and the enemies will be enter and bash away until one of you run out of things to bash. There is one strategy - Get artillery on everything since it has the longest range and you'll usually be able to win. No random events, no area modifiers.The ground combat follows the same route, though it has squares in a big square instead. Terrain is not included so just gear up with rifles, medikit and sidearm of choice and slaughter your enemies since they will just go for nearest enemy.The artwork is mostly reused from Stardrive 1 with a few new additions.The ship customization has been downsized as you can no longer turn mounts the way you desire or at least I've yet to find a way to do it - Do feel free to enlighten me if I'm wrong here, I'd love to find it.I've found no way to adjust my fleets in deployment outside of individual click'n'drag - Quite a bother since entering space-fights is (at the very least, more if you play warmongerer) half of what you do in this game.The UI is simplified beyond usability. Since both left and right buttons can be used for orders, you'll be giving contraorders repeatedly and watch action points waste away as troops run around when you tried to click the enemy to find out what gear he had - Or, perish the thought, deselect your current unit.I don't know if anyone else bothered building construction ships since the stations seem pretty much a waste of production - But I'd love to know if there's a way to delete a station? Since they instant deployed rather than let you target, I ended up with one blocking my capitol and it was a real nuisance.I've tried to remain objective here, but as I try and figure out anything positive about this game against others, I fail.Everyone has the colonization section and I'd recommend Stardrive 1 since it has a lot more entertaining elements.The one positive thing I can think of about this game is that the loading screen when starting the game looks really, really nice and is animated."
