,Recommended,252450,33918974,Posted: 30 July,all,AbonZel,"Whether or not to recommend this game is a very difficult decision to make for me.I truly enjoyed this game. I enjoy the shipbuilding and playing around with all the components and designs and how it allowed me to try different builds. I liked how some hulls had special benefits to them, like one hull gave a bonus to armor placed in it and another one that gave a large damage boost to beam weapons, and if you didn't want those, probably due to the increase in production cost, you could stick with the bonus-less hulls. I also loved a lot of the writing, as this game is not a ""serious"" game. A lot of the interactions with other races and events are funny, and there are a lot of references to other media, like Stargate, Masters of Orion, Futurama, and even Ghostbusters.However, the game is significantly unpolished and very buggy. For example, when I auto finished a space battle, if my fleet was large enough, I couldn't scroll all the way down to see if all the ships survived. At first, when I tried to see what a research topic was, the tooltip was hidden behind the research screen so I couldn't read most of it. When going to the next turn, if you were colonizing a planet and invading another, the screens would appear at the same time. All minor things, just little nuisances.There are also a lot of bugs, some bigger problems than others. Sometimes, even when I have surplus food and freighters to move the food to starving planets, those planets still starve. I can have deep space stations next to a sector and the sector can have full influence, but I still don't gain control over it. Various bugs that I've seen on the forums that still haven't been fixed. Thankfully, most of these bugs, while they do affect certain aspects of gameplay, they are pretty much never, in my experience, game breaking, and usually pretty easy to deal with or doesn't hurt too much.Like I said, even with those issues, I still enjoyed the game. If you have a low tolerance for bugs and general lack of polish, then I would say you should pass on this game. I would probably suggest that you try other 4X space games like Stellaris before trying this, but if you've tried most of those games or this one goes on a really good sale, I would probably say you can give it a try."
,Not Recommended,252450,21621368,"Posted: 4 March, 2016",all,Griffolion,"Tl;Dr - Just get Master of Orion 2, or the latest one.I really enjoyed the first StarDrive because of the real-time 4X. Despite the bugs in the first game, it was amazing seeing your empire come to life in real time. Ship customisation was a really cool thing, being able to build your ship from scratch from a general hull type is really cool.Basically the only cool thing that was transferred to SD2 was the ship building mechanic, and it received next to no improvements anyway. It went from real-time to turn based, and in doing so basically became a MoO clone. It tried to differentiate with an XCOM/HoM&M style ground combat mini-game where you could control your units. However it was such a half-baked and often buggy experience that it detracted far more than it could ever give.SD3 if there is going to be one, needs to return to its real-time roots, which was its biggest USP, as far as I'm concerned. The series has a chance to really make a mark in the space 4X genre, and it's unfortunate the second entry in the series has been so let down with lazy copy-cat design."
