76561197995359996,Recommended,252450,15361056,"Posted: 14 April, 2015",all,jdwilbanks,"Having played StarDrive one and being pretty impressed (After all, lets consider both of these games are by a one man band who gets alittle bit of art help on the side) but left wanting more, I had been following StarDrive 2 with alot of interest. I bought it day one, and started playing.As evidenced by nearly 90 hours into the game over the last week, I have been blown away. As many have noted, there's a real ""hardness"" level to the AI - even on easy; recent patches (which by the way, what developer do you know puts out 4 patches in 2 days, and works over a weekend?) have added a true easy mode, but I was honestly unchallanged by it - even normal mode with special events turned off felt too easy. Having a real challenge is fun - regardless (again to the folks complaining about the AI cheating) of how the AI accomplishes the challenge. I actually have to design ships specifically to take out each race's ships - its pretty neat in my mind that I can tool up a bunch of ships with long range weapons, shred the enemy, and then get owned by the next group because I don't have enough point defense and they have tons of carriers with swarms of hundreds of fighters.The graphics are outstanding; the game is filled with easter eggs to various Sci-Fi tropes; almost to the point I'm afriad some annoying lawyer will pop up and sue Zero. Some of them are aboslutely hysterical - such as the human fighter pilot hero.Sound is good; the real time battles are fun and engaging, and tactics really do matter.There's some bugs in Stardrive 2, but I'm confident Zero will get rid of them, and I also believe he will update and improve the already outstanding game over the next 6 months. I'm looking forward to modding it and doing some neat things.My final comment on StarDrive 2 is this - it is the kind of game that makes me say ""5 more minutes"", and in my mind, the best compliment a game can be payed is the ""5 more minutes"" feeling - its the halmark of a great game.There are many games out there that cost 50 bucks and are nowhere near as fun, enjoyable, technically sound, and replayable. Get StarDrive 2 today!"
76561197997932146,Recommended,252450,15687955,"Posted: 4 May, 2015",all,ig_Jan / Quarant1ne,"If you love 4x games (like me), you can't really go wrong here. Stardrive 2 steals features unapologetically from games like Master of Orion, Endless Space and of course Stardrive 1. It also tries to add some new depth to the XCOM style ground combat and the event-driven campaign.All that being said, it's not very polished. There are (slight) bugs as well as balancing issues and the ""random encounters"" aren't random at all, but always appear in the same order. I actually found the relatively small amount of ship modules refreshing, since your choices are more meaningful if there aren't thousands of options. What I'm missing are more planetary modules, more diplomacy options and a better end-game."
