76561197964882597,Recommended,252450,15398114,"Posted: 16 April, 2015",all,Kazzamkablam,"Stardrive 2 has more than few influences from grandfather of space strategies, Master of Orion 2. If you have played it you will feel instantly at home with how colony building and allocating population works, switching them between farmers, workers and scientists.Planets themselves come from several types, from Toxic wasteland to Gaia type planets and asteroid fields which can hold different amounts of population, which can be upgraded with technology. Tech tree itself is set so you have several fields to pick from and you can only pick one, leaving the other two to be obtained other ways, namely diplomacy and spying.Diplomacy itself gives you ""point"" limit with determines how much you can do with other races which increases as you do deals with the race. Eventually allowing you to do treaties such as non agression pact and alliance. Unfortunately AI and limited amount of victory conditions ingame undermine diplomacy a bit and sooner or later (usually sooner, due aggressive AI). You will end up fighting with the AI, which especially at harder difficulties can be brutal. On my playhtoughs I saw AI wield sneak attack fleet that was larger than my entire fleet.Space combat itself is a mix original Master of Orion 2 and rts, you equip your ships with different equipment and then command them in real time view which for the most part works smoothly but one of games issues is that it does not have reinforcement system, so with larger battles your computer can slow down to a crawl. Once you win space battle it's time to bring in the ground troops, which too can be equipped and heroes to be hired who can directly help you with ground combat.Ground combat itself is turn based system bit like X-Com except much simpler where you command your troops and your mechs until one side gets killed, problem with ground combat is AI is bit stupid and it can be easily exploited, I had same squad of 6 timid warriors (they receive penalty to hitpoints) and I was still able to eliminate most of enemy fights without losing single soldier due AI being poor at ground combat. It really needs to use it's special abilities and formations better.Lategame when your empire starts to expand on several starsystems and you have lots of colonies one of games biggest issues start to shine, there is no way to have manager for colonies which would build stuff based on your preferences, so you end up changing build orders a LOT, even when you have them queued it gets tedious and you really wish for some kind of governor system.Overall good game that could use some polish, especially quality of life improvements."
