,Recommended,252450,16104936,"Posted: 31 May, 2015",all,black_dragon74,"Stardrive 2 is an unapologetic Master of Orion clone that seeks to stay true to the classic standard of space 4X games. Besides a great number of direct references (Kulrathi? Really?) mechanics, buildings, and technologies taken directly from Master of Orion 2, there are more subtle parallels such as the occasional menace of the ""Masters"", which appears from sudden and inexplicable rifts to harass you for no apparent reason and give you problems in case you're not busy fighting anybody.And surprisingly, it stacks up pretty well. The array of different races are colorful and the differences between them are substantial. The space combat is fun, and expansion requires difficult and meaningful choices.Two areas in which Stardrive surpasses Orion is in ship design and diplomacy. When making ships, you don't just decide on modules and heap them onto a ship until some arbitrary ""mass limit"" is reached. Rather, ships each have a footprint, and modules - which include everything from weapons to engines to less obviously useful ""capacitors"" take up space, energy, and have mass, which slows the ship down. There are a lot of implications resulting from this, but the simplest is that you can choose to focus on speed, defense, or firepower without having specific technologies specifically suited to each area. Just pile on more armor, more engines, or bigger guns. Diplomacy is quite streamlined, with each offer being given a straight value that needs to be matched or exceeded for the deal to go through. Meanwhile, a species ""tolerance level"" keeps you from making very large deals, which is a very interesting and thoughtful cap on inter-empire trading.Other areas in Stardrive 2 fall a bit short of their promise. Ground combat consists of a clunky lineup of a handful of soldiers in simple, turn-based combat, and it's quite hard to imagine such small and low-octane encounters deciding the ownership of entire planets. The technology tree also seems a bit stunted, and could use a few tiers that only offer one technology to research; some very important technologies simply should be acquired as a matter of course, such as battleships and terraforming. Nobody would seriously give up a larger ship footprint for a larger starbase or improved armor plating. It's also strange that there's only one ship footprint for each ship size, which changes from species to species. It's hardly unthinkable that ships built for different purposes would have different basic frames, but we have to settle for simply filling them with different modules. Also missing from Stardrive is a government system; all races apparently have the same system of managing their empires, modified by their species. Finally, BUGS. Lots of bugs. And not in the sense of an insectoid, hive-mind species (curiously, the Klackons didn't make it into this MOO clone). Things like ships suddenly taking on the appearance of other species' ships, fleets vanishing, sometimes being unable to name new ship designs, and - my favorite - being assaulted by an enemy race and then being given control of their troopers while the computer controls my soldiers. None of them are game-breaking, but you're not going to get through the game without finding a few of your own.There are a lot of other things that could have simply used MORE. The planet types are stripped straight from MOO (toxic, radiated, barren, desert, all the way to gaia) with no interesting new alien-ish worlds on offer. There are neat little mini-quests and mysterious objects in space to explore, but they're exactly the same from game to game and quickly run out. Space combat is a lot of fun, but ships could use more tactical settings other than ""frontal attack/broadside"" and ""sit in place/move"". There's an engagement zone setting, but the blasted thing resets from encounter to encounter, so if you have a preferred setting (plasma cannons are infamously useless at long range) you have to reset it in each new combat. And as far as I can tell, there are no sudden galactic events that affect all players equally, such as space monsters or subspace shutdowns. A missed opportunity.That said, Stardrive 2 is still a great game, and stacks up to its ancestor admirably. But I'll be looking ahead to StarDrive 3 (and hope that in that respect it is NOT like Master of Orion)."
,Recommended,252450,15487143,"Posted: 21 April, 2015",all,DodgerRoger,"Another of the Futuristic Galaxy Empire building games, I only picked this up a couple of weeks ago and from what I can tell it seems to be one of the better ones (if not the best for space combat).There are a few rough edges, the ground combat looks and behaves quite poorly compared to that in space. For the larger space battles you'd need a beast of a pc to run it on maximum settings and the lack of multiplayer is another weakness.Though for those who enjoy this genre, I can't help but recommend it, if only for the space combat, design and of course the Owlwoks! ;)"
