,Recommended,252450,15917388,"Posted: 20 May, 2015",all,"Testiclees the Mighty, Ph.D.","If you are a child of the early 80's or late 70's, you may remember Master's of Orion II. It was, for lack of a better term, a masterpiece. The graphics were worse than the modern game FTL, but at the time that was the standard. And in this game, that didn't matter: You were the commander of a space empire with distinct characteristics. You designed spaceships, sent them into battle, researched exciting new technologies, and negotiated with other empires for exchange of goods, technologies and money.The Good: Stardrive II is a modern reinvention of that game. It does nothing to reinvent the 4X genre, but the execution is the closest thing to the old Masters of Orion II that any game has in recent history. Trust me, I've played them all. This game gets some things brilliantly right, however: Turns play out at a pace you set, either calculated and one at a time, or mash the turn button and let it run for a few turns. Space combat is semi-real time, while ground combat is turn based. Outside of certain scenarios, they are also auto-calculable, which is nice at times-- Battle can feel slowly paced, and skipping it can be appealing.The Bad: The game is also riddled with bugs and poor interface decisions. Hero's skills, like ""Bloodthirsty,"" which allows a hero to gain passive governing bonuses for every enemy defeated in ground combat, doesn't work at all. Loot, which gives you bonus BC (money) doesn't either. Occaisional crashes happen, and the game doesn't support multi-monitors or borderless windows. Ground combat is also tedious, and it can be easy to make an uncorrectable mistake that costs you a battle due to the poor interface.MOO Fans will enjoy the fact that most of the old species play style can be recreated, despite certain traits not being present in the default characteristics. Creativity, for example, allows you to research every technology in a tier, just like MOO2 Psilons-- but requires taking a lot of negative traits to achieve, like low gravity homeworld.I can't say that this game will be appealing to a newer audience. But if you loved MOO2, you'll love Stardrive 2."
76561197977744657,Recommended,252450,15900824,"Posted: 19 May, 2015",all,MagicSquid,"Equal parts frustration and glorious triumph. 4/5, would frustrate again."
76561198024044668,Recommended,252450,17805383,"Posted: 30 August, 2015",all,denstjames,I really like it so far. Its not a perfect game but I have not had any serious glitches. I am running this on windows 10 also. i saw a post saying that it did not run under windows 10 right after I bought while it was downloading and was thinking I was going to have to request a refund but its worked perfectly.The ground combat can be a little clunky and not everything is explained but I like the questing system and the tech tree where you have to make choices on what tech you want rather than having a static tree where you get everything and you always know the best path.The combat system is pretty good also. I have played some 4x games where you have run every action and some that are just viewers while this one takes the best of both. You design your ships to do a function and then in combat you can pick targets in real time and pause it but do not have to micro manage each action each ship is going to take so you can have large fleets.
