76561197976579682,Not Recommended,252450,15343843,"Posted: 13 April, 2015",all,Tkul,"[On the DLC]Here we go a year later and the same problems. Original release originally stabilized a bit to get rid of some of the game breaking bugs, not all or most but some, but along comes a DLC to reintroduce problems that were solved right along side a whole slew of new issues. Diplomacy is still nonexistant, the shipyard still bugs out randomly though you can usually correct them by scrapping and remaking the designs until it decides to validate them properly. Combat is about the same as before, mash your ships into their ships and hope your ships are tougher.  AI is still super aggressive to almost unreasonable lengths, and the nonfaction AI recieved some inflated numbers to add to the fun. Would not recommend, and be warned if you bought the DLC you won't be able to refund it if you had time in the base game as the refund system does not count the DLC as a separate purchase.[On the Original Release]I really wanted to like this game, I bought the first one and was excited for the sequel but much like the original the sequel was released too soon.  The game is still fairly buggy, which isn't necessarily a deal breaker most of the time but it has a terrible tendency to freeze on loading screens or the GNN videos that pop up occasionally.   The shipyard interface also tends to bug out occasionally and mark your ships as invalid due to not having met criteria that you clearly have i.e. Requiring you to add ammo cannisters to pure energy ships.Outside of the bugs, some of which are game breaking (freezing on load screens) but mostly just annoying (shipyard bugs) you also need to deal with artificially inflated difficulty.  The AI opponents clearly cheat, it doesn't even attempt to hide the fact that they do it, which again is not normally a deal breaker, but the AI is also incredibly aggressive and the diplomacy setup is almost impossible out in front of due to it restricting what deals you can accept using the same mechanics it uses for the AI.   You will frequently find yourself staring down multiple full fleets of enemy units that are generally 2-3 tech tiers up on you before you expand much past your initial system.  If you invest in expanding you're just going to end up losing the expansions to random occurance since pirates and rebels will also randomly pop up with large fleets to take them over.Over all it has potential but it's really more frustrating than it's worth to fight your way past the bugs just to have to try to game the inflated advantages that the AI gets."
